> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tim1965>Tim1965</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/02 2:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=674.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Star travel</span><hr size=1> We can build a crewed  Orion Thermonuclear starship today,  if we want to do this .Orion can reach about 10% of light velocity.Orion is 100 % within our capabilities.This has been feasible for 40 years.<br>
 <br>
 We can not yet make a large crewed starship <br>
go faster then 10% of light speed . But we can go 10%<br>
of light speed as I have said. That is enough to get us to Alpha Centauri within 40 to 50 years.<br>
<br>
 We also can make a small low mass  solar/laser/maser powered solar sail propelled robot space probe that can go nearly as fast as the speed of light to the stars.<br>
<br>
 It is impractical to use this to propell a crewed starship because of the excessive laser/maser energy requirements . It is 100 % within our current capabilities<br>
to send something like the voyager or pioneer robot space probes to the stars in this way however.<br>
Tim <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/02 12:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=674.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Star travel</span><hr size=1> I'm not exactly sure we [i]should[/i] send anything to Alpha Centauri for the time being.  In all honesty, sending something there would most likely yield little economic benefit and suck up a lot of resources that could be spent on more lucrative options such as space colonies and asteroid mining ventures.  Such things would probably be much more valuable for the cost of such resources.<br>
<br>
As far as interstellar exploration, leave that to self-replicating Von Neumann Probes which will hopefully become possible at the end of the century when we have mastered nanotech replication and fusion drive.  This would allow a very efficient and cost effective way to map our corner of the galaxy in a spherical radius fashion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 609<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/02 1:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=674.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Star travel</span><hr size=1> If we did send human colonists on a one way trip to a habitable extra-solar planet in the near future (perhaps on a generational-style Orion) they would have to live very low tech on the planet's surface since they couldn't really maintain a lot of today's technology for manufacturing the spare parts they would need and keeping advanced power systems fueled up.  The colonists might just live off the land the way Native Americans did.  I could see the original Orion and its occupants becoming mythologized in the views of very distant descendents who are still in a pre-industrial or agrarian style society.  I doubt if the knowledge of the initial colonists would last.  It would probably have to be rediscovered by their distant descendents.  To change course, if we could discover how to put people in suspended animation or learn to transplant our minds into machines I think an Orion could make a suitable craft for getting out around 20+ light years since that would only take 200 years.  Not a long time if some people are correct in thinking that the human lifespan might be extended to thousands of years.   Von Neuman machines are good for exploring but I think it's possible a number of people will want to leave the Solar Sytem entirely within the next few hundred years.      <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/02 1:48 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=674.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Star travel</span><hr size=1> we could theoretically include a nuclear generator on the ship, and basic tools for extracting fuels.  they would not have to start from scratch...we could put a human database onto dvds (which can hold 10 gbs of data each), including all blueprints and manuals and books of the human knowledge and past.  even assuming it takes 1,000 cds, this is still a pittance of weight, and it would be a tremendously useful guide for any celestial explorers.  if we could build an orion large enough, it could be a floating city, with schools, crops, etc.  <br>
<br>
with advanced biogenetics, we could engineer easier to grow crops and all kinds of other things.  our pioneers needn't start from scratch. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 305<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/31/02 5:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=674.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Star travel</span><hr size=1> At .1C, it'll take impractically long to get there. Even if we can make the ship, we don't yet know enough to let them survive that long. Need lots of practice living in space before then.<br>
 Better to use the big Orion ships to plant seed factories to build the infrastructure to build space colonies.<br>
<br>
If you can't afford the time and investment to build the kind of infrastructure to build laser-pushed interstellar missions to get the crew there &amp; back again, then you're in the wrong business. Interstellar travel isn't for a quick &amp; cheap solution.<br>
 Makes far more sense to do it this way than to use bombs to push more bombs which will be used to push more bombs which will be used to push more bombs which will be used to push more bombs which will be used to push more bombs... (love copy &amp; paste when describing how rockets work)<br>
 The old rocket equation eats you up if you're trying to go to another star -even using H-bombs.<br>
 .1 C is wimpy. Face it; Orion doesn't make a good starship.<br>
<br>
 With the big Orion ships, we could plant colonies out in the Oort cloud easily.<br>
 No problems with self-sustinence if you've got the Oort bodies to mine for volatiles.<br>
 These far-flung colonies could also add to the long baseline interferometry telescope we build up with habitats all over the solar system. This lets us <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">see</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> planetary systems at nearby stars, as well as map our own cometary halo, and some of the interstellar comets.<br>
<br>
If the Sun's too dim so far out, build a bigger mirror (it's only metal foil...)<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://ssi.org/assets/images/Ch08p125.gif">colony at Earth/Moon orbits<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://ssi.org/assets/images/Ch08p125tn.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://ssi.org/assets/images/Ch12p265.gif">colony past Pluto's orbit<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://ssi.org/assets/images/Ch12p265tn.gif"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
These from the book &quot;the High Frontier&quot;. About that colony out at Pluto; What the book talks about, is establishing a somewhat arbitrary &quot;continental shelf&quot; for our solar system. They stipulated that an average per-capita energy resource about like the modern US is desired, and then said that they'd limit the mass of the mirror to no more than 2X the habitat (at several wavelengths of light thickness, for metal foil).<br>
 The answer came out somewhere like 4 light-days -far beyond Pluto, beyond the heliopause, in interstellar space but well within the Sun's cometary cloud. (plenty of ices out there to live on)<br>
 With all that (more mass than the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>entire rest of the solar system combined</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> out there, within a few light-days), I question the fundamental need to go to other stars -for the time being, anyway, and with people.<br>
 Probes, sure.<br>
<br>
Nuclaeon<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; I'm not exactly sure we </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->should<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> send anything<br>
to Alpha Centauri for the time being...<br>
&gt;... sending something there would most likely yield<br>
little economic benefit and suck up a lot of resources<br>
that could be spent on more lucrative options such as<br>
space colonies and asteroid mining ventures.<br>
&gt; Such things would probably be much more valuable for<br>
the cost of such resources.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Remember though that the first Star Wisp probes can be sent as the tests of the early SPS arrays... A couple decades later, as they near the target star, we've got more SPS arrays to use to flood the system with energy for the probe to use in building up detailed pictures.<br>
So they effectively don't cost anything, and fit right in with everything else we're doing.<br>
<br>
Besides, I don't think anybody's arguing about the economic benefits of interstellar missions... If it can be done, it's by a rich spacefaring civilization.<br>
<br>
edited to add:<br>
<br>
All this adds up to nomadic interstellar colonies.<br>
 Colonies out in the Oort cloud can spread all the way out there. We suspect that the cloud of cometary bodies attached to our Sun goes out to 1.5 light years or more. They mix freely with interstellar comets, and maybe even into &amp; through the loose cloud of stuff attached to other stars.<br>
 All you need for a rich &amp; full ife out there is a mirror. If you don't limit yourself to a relatively low-mass for the mirror, you can go out that far. Out there, the Sun is only a particularly bright star, and there are others brighter.<br>
 If all it takes to latch onto a cometary body which isn't orbiting this star is a few hundred meters/second, and you have a few decades to match velocities, then it doen't even take a nuclear engine. The entire colony moves on an electric engine powered by the mirror, and fueled by rock dust from the mine tailings. (The Nuclear pulse engines are reseved for sending people and quick emergency supplies out that far in less than a lifetime.)<br>
<br>
 This kind of interstellar travel has real economic incentive -for the people doing it. No huge solar system wide infrastructure to build a city sized ship costing more than the entire planet makes in a decade -to send out a piddling slow generation ship which can't even refuel or supply itself in between and may not survive that long.<br>
It doesn't matter to these people if somebody a century later passes them by. They're not interested in a destination -except the next comet body.<br>
